        <h1>Workout Information</h1>
        <h2>
            Workout Information
        </h2>
        <p>We have many different workouts available to each user. On this page you can read about each workout, what equipment you may need, the muscle(s) it targets, 
            and how to perform each workout.</p>
        <h3>
            Bench
        </h3>
            <p>
                For bench press exercises you will need either a barbell with weights or dumbbells along with a bench to lay down on. 
                Your chest and triceps are targeted during this exercise. To perform the exercise, lay down on the bench, lower the weight(s) to your chest, 
                and then extend your arms with the weight for each rep.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Incline Bench
        </h3>
            <p>
                This is a variation of the bench press where the bench is lifted at an angle (under 90 degrees).
            </p>
        <h3>
            Bicep Curls
        </h3>
            <p>
                Dumbbells or other weights are needed for this exercise. It targets the bicep. Hold each dumbbell with arms relaxed.
                For each rep: bend your arm at the elbow bringing the dumbbell up and towards yourself with your palms facing yourself.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Sit-ups
        </h3>
            <p>
                Sit ups require some weight for your feet or a friend can hold your feet. Your abdominal muscles are the target of this exercise. 
                Lay on your back with some counter weight on your feet and your knees bent. For each rep bring your chest to your knees without swinging your arms.
                Side crunches are a variation of sit-ups where you lay on your side, with knees bent, and attempt to bring your torso (the side facing upwards) to your hip.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Lat Pull Downs
        </h3>
            <p>
                You will need access to a lat pull down machine for this exercise. It targets your back muscles. Sit down on the bench and reach up to handle. 
                Pull the handle down to the top of your chest for each rep.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Lateral Raises
        </h3>
            <p>
                Dumbbells or other free weights are necessary for this exercise. It targets your shoulders and specifically the medial deltoids. 
                While standing hold your dumbbells in both hands with arms at your side. While keeping your arms extended, raise them up your side to shoulder level and back down.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Leg Press
        </h3>
            <p>
                A leg press machine is used for this exercise. The leg press focuses on the quadriceps. Sit down in the machine and move the weight bringing your knees toward your
                chest and then extending your legs.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Pushups
        </h3>
            <p>
                No weight need for this exercise, but you can put a weight on your back. Pushups primarily work the pectoral muscles but also work the triceps, shoulders, and abdominals.
                Start a pushup by laying on your stomach with your legs together. Place your palms on the ground next to your chest push your body up until your arms are extended. Bring your
                body back down close to the ground before going back up. 
            </p>
        <h3>
            Deadlift
        </h3>
            <p>
                A barbell with weights is needed for this exercise. Deadlifts are a compound exercise that works the hamstrings, abdominals, glutes, quads, and traps. Start with the barbell on the ground.
                While keeping your arms and back straight, pick up the barbell while keeping it as close to your body as possible. Place the bar back on the ground for every rep. RDLs are a deadlift variation 
                where the barbell starts at the hips and the focus is on the downwards motion. The user leans farther forward for this variation. 
            </p>
        <h3>
            Squat
        </h3>
            <p>
                Squats can be done with just body weight, a barbell on your shoulders, or free weights in  your hands. Squats targets your glutes and quads. For the default squat
                you want to keep your feet shoulder width apart and your back straight. Move straight down by bending at your knees until your thighs are parallel with the ground before returning to standing position.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Overhead Press
        </h3>
            <p>
                Overhead Press can be done with free weights or a barbell. Your shoulders, triceps, and traps.
                Place your feet shoulder width apart. Hold the weight(s) at shoulder height and push over your head until your arms are extended for every rep. 
            </p>
        <h3>
            Leg Curls
        </h3>
            <p>
                A leg curl machine is necessary. Your hamstrings are the primary target, but your calves can also be worked. Lay on your stomach, on the machine, with your legs under the padded bar. 
                For every rep, curl your heels to your glutes.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Leg Extensions
        </h3>
            <p>
                A leg extension machine is needed. Leg extensions focus on your quads. Sit down on the machine with your lower leg under the padded bar.
                Kick your feet so that your legs are extended for every rep.
                
            </p>
        <h3>
            Plank
        </h3>
            <p>
                Planks target your ab muscles along with shoulders. There are multiple variations of planks. You can perform straight arm, elbow, or side planks. For a straight arm plank, 
                start by laying on the ground. Push up so that your arms are extended and feet together. Keep your body in a straight line from your feet to you head and hold. 
            </p>
        <h3>
            Mountain Climbers
        </h3>
            <p>
                Mountain climbers are a cardio exercise that targets your ab muscles and shoulders. Start in a arm extended plank position. For every rep, try to bring one knee up towards your chest and alternate.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Tricep Extensions
        </h3>
            <p>
                Tricep extensions can be done with a tricep extension machine or dumbells. As named, this exercise targets your tricepts. For a standing tricep extension with dumbbells, hold the dumbell(s) 
                behind your head and press up until your arms are extended. 
            </p>
        <h3>
            Lunges
        </h3>
            <p>
                Lunges can be done with body weight, barbell, or dumbbells. The focus is on your legs, primarily on your quads and glutes. For every variation, while standing step either forward or backward. 
                Move your move straight down until your leading foot is parallel with the ground before pressing back up.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Calf Raises
        </h3>
            <p>
                Calf raises are typical down with a calf raise machine. This exercise focuses on your calves. Stand in the machine with your shoulders under the pads with the first third of your foot on the bottom of the machine. 
                Raise upward by moving onto your toes for every rep and back down.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Pullups
        </h3>
            <p>
                Pullups can be done with bodyweight, weight strapped to the hips, or assisted with a machine or exercise bands. Pullups focus on your back muscles. Place your hands on the pullup bar a little wider than 
                shoulder width. While keeps your body straight, pull your chin up the top of the bar.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Rowing Exercises
        </h3>
            <p>
                Standard bent over rows use a barbell. Rowing exercises target your back. With the bar at the hips lean forward and let your arms hang with the bar. Pull the bar straight back towards your chest.
                Single arm rows use a dumbell with your one arm and knee (same side) on a bench. Lean over the bench and leg your arm with the dumbell hang. Pull the dumbell back past your chest for every rep. 
                Seated rows use a cable machine where you can sit and pull the cable handle staright back towards yourself.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Shrugs
        </h3>
            <p>
                Shrugs are typically done with a barbell but free weights are also used. The primary target is your traps. Hold the weights at your waist. While keeping your arms extended, lift the weights 
                upwards by bringing your shoulders up to your ears.
            </p>
        <h3>
            Dips
        </h3>
            <p>
                Dips can be done with bodyweight, weight tied to the waist, or assisted with exercise bands or a machine. Every variation requires a place to put your hands with space in between and underneath 
                for your body. Start by placing your hands on the intended posts. Lift of the ground with your arms extended. Lower your body 
                down and press back up for every rep.
            </p>
    
